https://www.linkedin.com/posts/systemdesignengineer_system-design-engineer-weekly-recap-activity-7354463819693264896-H9pA?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAADEtMvQBOS82FNYVBA08XS2Istc-XujcVQc

Here‚Äôs one of the practical questions they might throw at you:
‚ÄúHow would you design a distributed backup system that avoids backing up the same data again and again?‚Äù

Think beyond basics:
 ‚úÖ Use content-defined chunking ‚Äî smartly split files to detect small changes
 ‚úÖ Generate fingerprints (hashes) to identify duplicate chunks
 ‚úÖ Store unique chunks only once across all backups
 ‚úÖ Build scalable indexing ‚Äî maybe using bloom filters or sharded stores

All to ensure storage efficiency without sacrificing recovery speed.

But let‚Äôs talk trade-offs ‚Äî
 What happens if two backup jobs hit the same file at the same time?
 ‚ùì Do you lock writes?
 ‚ùì Go lock-free but clean up later?

Rubrik interviews often explore these edge cases ‚Äî your choices and your fallbacks.

